p: We analyzed the YFV vector competence of 22 Ae. malayensis and 31 Ae. aegypti 14 days after oral exposure to an infectious blood meal containing 1.84 ×10 6 FFU/ml of YFV. The IR was 45.5% (10/22) and 96.8% (30/31) for Ae. malayensis and Ae. aegypti, respectively (Fig. 2) and the difference between the two species was statistically significant ( p < 0.001). The DR was 10% (1/10) and 36.7% (11/30) for Ae. malayensis and Ae. aegypti, respectively (Fig. 2), and the difference between the two species was not statistically significant ( p = 0.087). The TR was 0% (0/1) and 9.1% (1/11) for Ae. malayensis and Ae. aegypti, respectively (Fig. 2), and the difference between the two species could not be statistically tested because there was only 1 Ae. malayensis female and thus no replication. Overall, there was no evidence for a statistically significant difference ( p = 0.297) in vector competence between the two species, as TE was 0% (0/22) and 3.2% (1/31) for Ae. malayensis and Ae. aegypti, respectively (Fig. 2). However, the very small proportion of positive saliva samples overall (a single Ae. aegypti saliva sample was found positive) limited our ability to detect differences. Together, these data do not conclusively demonstrate the YFV vector competence of Ae. malayensis, but suggest that it is likely lower than that of the Ae. aegypti control population.
